{"candidates": [{"content": "{\"claim\": \"Harness strictly beats self-consistency iff the pool contains a non-empty set of questions whose SC winner is wrong but critic recall on those items > 0 while critic precision is high enough that the expected count of correctly-won questions falsely flagged does not exceed the count of wrong-winner questions truly flagged and recoverable.\", \"mechanism\": \"Let R = recall on wrong-SC-winner items, P = precision on right-SC-winner items, n_w = count of wrong-SC-winners, n_r = count of right-SC-winners. Harness net gain = R*n_w - [(1-P)*n_r]*(prob_flagged_right_question_flips_to_wrong). Strict advantage requires R*n_w > false-flag harm. False flags only hurt when they flip a correct majority to incorrect; this probability depends on majority margin. So the operative precision is not pool-wide but precision-weighted-by-flip-vulnerability. The mid-zone 1/(k+1) < e < 0.5 is where wrong winners exist and some correct winners have thin margins, making both terms nonzero.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"mid-zone base error where some SC winners are wrong AND some correct winners have thin margins\", \"critic recall > 0 on wrong-winner items\", \"critic precision high enough that false flags on thin-margin correct winners do not outnumber true flags on wrong winners\"]}, \"excludes\": [\"e <= 1/(k+1): no wrong SC winners exist, harness cannot gain\", \"e >= 0.5: SC majority wrong, critic precision becomes critical but SC baseline already broken\", \"critic recall = 0: no wrong winners recoverable\", \"critic precision so low that false flips >= true fixes\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"At k=5, e in [0.15, 0.35], critic with precision >= 0.7 and recall >= 0.5: harness accuracy is NOT strictly greater than SC accuracy, measured as harness_acc - sc_acc > 0 on >= 60% of studies\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"At k=5, e in [0.15, 0.35], critic with precision < 0.5 and recall >= 0.5: harness accuracy is strictly greater than SC (refuting the precision-gate prediction)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"False flags on correct-SC-winner items with margin >= 3 votes do not cause answer flips at rate > 10%, confirming that only thin-margin correct winners are vulnerable\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"The predicted threshold precision >= 1 - R*n_w / (n_r * flip_prob) is empirically violated: harness still gains with precision below threshold or fails above it\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"Supersedes 5b9a8d2c753d by grounding the regime boundary in the causal mechanism (flag-and-flip arithmetic) rather than raw precision/recall values. The measured v4-pro hard-set data (recall 1.0, precision 0.125, net 0) is explained: n_w=0 since SC=1.00, so R*n_w=0 regardless of recall; false flags on n_r items existed but did not flip because margins were >= 4 (only 1 error per question). The v4-flash easy-set (precision 0.333, recall 0.25, net 0) is explained: n_w was 1 (base error 0.033, k=5), so at most 1 recoverable item, but recall 0.25 gives expected 0.25 recoveries while low precision generates false flags that offset. Experiment: 500 questions across 4 base-error tiers (0.1, 0.2, 0.3, 0.4), k=5 and k=7, 3 critic configurations (high-P/low-R, low-P/high-R, balanced), ~60k tokens per tier-k-critic cell, 12 cells, ~720k tokens total — trimmed to 4 core cells at ~240k tokens.\"}", "refs": [{"target": "c9386a6c7b3038d7ebaf9f80aed2b6bfd17ad2be03ed64556d0173f0d0085495", "role": "dependence"}, {"target": "862de34bced36d488ac299f984c270812db349a12e50b3acf126462c0be93e72", "role": "dependence"}, {"target": "495c5963dafbd26bf2aa1838491e8428005b9a54825f21a8df1e5ead37908e7a", "role": "dependence"}], "typicality": 0.85}, {"content": "{\"claim\": \"No fixed (base error, precision, recall, k) regime is sufficient; harness strictly beats SC only when the critic's per-question confidence is positively correlated with the SC winner being wrong, so that filtering selectively removes wrong-majority items more than right-majority items.\", \"mechanism\": \"Define critic-winner alignment A = P(critic flags | SC winner wrong) - P(critic flags | SC winner right). This is question-conditional and subsumes precision/recall, which are pool-level aggregates that wash out per-question signal. Harness strictly beats SC iff A > threshold, where threshold depends on the flip-vulnerability of correct winners. Two critics with identical pool-level precision and recall can have opposite A values: one flags wrong winners preferentially (A > 0, harness gains), the other flags randomly or anti-correlatedly (A <= 0, harness ties or loses). The measured data is explained: v4-pro hard-set had A undefined (no wrong winners to condition on), v4-flash easy-set had A near zero (critic flags uncorrelated with winner correctness, precision 0.333 means most flags hit correct winners).\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"question-conditional critic-winner alignment as the operative variable\", \"any base error rate where wrong SC winners exist (e > 1/(k+1))\", \"both high and low pool-level precision/recall, if alignment is favorable\"]}, \"excludes\": [\"claims that fixed (P, R) values alone predict harness advantage\", \"regimes where no wrong SC winners exist (e <= 1/(k+1))\", \"critics whose flagging is independent of winner correctness (A=0)\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Two critic configurations with matched pool-level precision ~0.5 and recall ~0.5 but different alignment A (A_high > 0.3 vs A_low < 0.1) produce statistically indistinguishable harness-vs-SC gaps, refuting the alignment thesis\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"A critic with higher alignment A but lower precision AND lower recall than another critic produces a larger harness-vs-SC gap, confirming alignment dominates precision/recall\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Alignment A > 0.3 does NOT produce strict harness advantage in >= 60% of studies when base error is in [0.15, 0.35], falsifying the A > threshold prediction\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"The correlation between A and harness-vs-SC gap across all study cells is r < 0.3, while the correlation between pool-level precision and the gap is r > 0.5, contradicting the subsumption claim\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"Extends c9386a6c and 30e483eb by proposing a specific measurable quantity (alignment A) and a decisive experiment that controls for precision/recall while varying alignment. The experiment uses 300 questions at a single base-error tier (e ~ 0.25, k=5) where wrong winners are guaranteed to exist, and generates 6 critic variants via different prompting strategies (e.g., 'flag if the answer seems too simple' vs 'flag if you detect a specific error type') that produce different alignment values at similar precision/recall. ~50k tokens per variant, 300k total. The counterexample-first stance is honored: the forbidden cases include direct refutations of the alignment thesis and tests of whether pool-level precision outperforms alignment as predictor.\"}", "refs": [{"target": "c9386a6c7b3038d7ebaf9f80aed2b6bfd17ad2be03ed64556d0173f0d0085495", "role": "dependence"}, {"target": "30e483eb494067d8323a796b7e319a77a3abce4c45ba08a487df2b6838e5082b", "role": "dependence"}, {"target": "495c5963dafbd26bf2aa1838491e8428005b9a54825f21a8df1e5ead37908e7a", "role": "dependence"}, {"target": "862de34bced36d488ac299f984c270812db349a12e50b3acf126462c0be93e72", "role": "dependence"}], "typicality": 0.75}, {"content": "{\"claim\": \"Harness strictly beats SC only when (i) base error e is in the majority-fragile zone 1/(k+1) < e < 1/2, (ii) critic precision P >= 1/2 (flags are more likely correct than not), AND (iii) critic recall R > 0; any one condition failing forces harness <= SC.\", \"mechanism\": \"Treat the system as majority-flip dynamics. When e <= 1/(k+1), SC never errs, so harness can only break correct answers. When e >= 1/2, SC majority is wrong, and harness may help but SC baseline is already below single-model, making 'beat SC' a trivially low bar. In the mid-zone, wrong SC winners exist (making recall necessary) and correct SC winners with thin margins exist (making precision necessary to avoid breaking them). P >= 1/2 is the coarse threshold: if over half of flags are wrong, the expected number of false flips exceeds true fixes given similar margins. This is a necessary-conjunction claim: all three conditions are individually necessary and jointly sufficient.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"majority-fragile zone 1/(k+1) < e < 1/2\", \"P >= 1/2 and R > 0 simultaneously\", \"k = 3, 5, 7 (odd k to avoid ties)\"], \"excludes\": [\"e <= 1/(k+1): no SC errors to fix\", \"e >= 1/2: SC trivially broken\", \"P < 1/2: false flags dominate\", \"R = 0: no true flags\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Any study cell with e in (1/(k+1), 1/2), P >= 1/2, R > 0 where harness_acc <= sc_acc, refuting joint sufficiency\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Any study cell with e in (1/(k+1), 1/2), P < 1/2, R > 0 where harness_acc > sc_acc, refuting P >= 1/2 necessity\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Any study cell with e in (1/(k+1), 1/2), P >= 1/2, R = 0 where harness_acc > sc_acc, refuting R > 0 necessity\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Any study cell with e <= 1/(k+1) where harness_acc > sc_acc, refuting the lower-bound necessity\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"The most falsifiable candidate: every condition is claimed necessary, so a single counterexample violating any one while still showing harness > SC kills the conjecture. The counterexample-first stance is maximally honored — each forbidden case is a specific violation. Experiment: 3 base-error tiers (0.1, 0.25, 0.4) x k in {3, 5, 7} x 4 critic configs spanning P in [0.2, 0.8] and R in [0, 0.8], 36 cells, ~8k tokens per cell using 50 questions each, ~288k tokens. The coarse P >= 1/2 threshold is the weakest link and the most likely to be refuted — a more refined version would make P threshold depend on margins, but that reduces falsifiability.\"}", "refs": [{"target": "862de34bced36d488ac299f984c270812db349a12e50b3acf126462c0be93e72", "role": "dependence"}, {"target": "495c5963dafbd26bf2aa1838491e8428005b9a54825f21a8df1e5ead37908e7a", "role": "dependence"}], "typicality": 0.6}]}